<TEXT>
a former aide in sen bob grahams office said 
monday he had arranged a meeting between bank regulators and 
centrust bank which later failed causing the biggest bailout of 
the savings and loan crisis 
nbc news reported monday that the aide steve josias had used 
his position as a special counsel in grahams office to bring 
pressure on bank regulators looking into the thrifts finances 
but josias denied the report and grahams office said the 
democratic senator had had no knowledge of the meeting 
josias fort lauderdale firm had handled some real estate 
matters for centrust before the 1987 meeting with officials from 
the federal home loan bank board said ken klein grahams 
spokesman 
the day after the meeting grahams office manager met with 
josias to tell him such a meeting was against the senators policy 
klein said graham himself did not learn of the meeting until 
earlier in 1990 and characterized it as poor judgment klein said 
we do not seek to intervene with regulators on specific 
cases klein said 
graham a member of the senate banking committee said in an 
interview from his washington dc office he had done nothing to 
delay the seizure of the miamibased thrift by the government the 
centrust bailout will cost taxpayers 17 billion 
i would say categorically my office did not have any effect 
on any action by federal regulators that would have affected their 
decisions graham said 
josias told the associated press that nbcs report was 
ludicrous he described himself as merely a convener of the 
30minute meeting centrust officials called it because they felt 
federal officials were failing to respond to questions on 
regulatory procedures he said 
josias worked in grahams office for six months as special 
counsel providing legal expertise klein said 
when lawyers called grahams office they were given to the 
lawyer josias said when asked about the centrust call that led 
to the meeting i should have said then that i know centrust and 
my legal firm did work for them 
when regulators seized centrust in february they blamed its 
failure on speculative investing including purchase of more than 
1 billion in junk bonds 
they also cited the lavish spending of the institutions 
chairman david l paul who spent millions of dollars of deposits 
on a museumquality art collection kept at his home a company 
yacht limousines a corporate jet and goldplated toilets in the 
executive washrooms paul has declined comment about centrust and 
its seizure 
a fraud squad of investigators is examining the legality of 
328000 in political contributions by paul 
graham said he has never received political contributions from 
paul or any centrust political action committees 
</TEXT>
