<TEXT>
for two years a city within a city lived 
and grew in the shadow of city hall 
then one morning in july buses pulled up to civic center plaza 
to take away the homeless people who camped under knobbybranched 
olive trees amid mildewed mattresses tattered blankets and 
shopping carts heaped with the eclectic possessions of modern 
nomads 
the homeless and their advocates decried the citys 
insensitivity 
its not that they care about these people not having homes 
said jill 28 who had been bouncing in and out of welfare hotels 
with her boyfriend ron for six months they just dont want 
them to be seen 
but mayor art agnos said he does care thats why he allowed the 
homeless to live in the park while he arranged a humane 
alternative two fullservice shelters equipped with everything 
from job training to drug counseling facilities designed to ease 
people off the street for good 
in cities across the nation city officials and advocates for 
the homeless talk about how public emotion hostility and 
compassion frustration and sympathy has escalated as the ranks 
of the homeless swell 
people are frustrated its not over were into quick fixes 
said mary ann gleason director of the denver healthcare for the 
homeless clinic which serves about 6500 people a year there 
are hundreds of thousands of people weve gotten off the streets 
but there are more falling in behind them 
no one knows how many americans are homeless estimates range 
from 300000 to 3 million but no one disputes the fact that the 
number is increasing and greater numbers mean greater visibility 
its a common perception that at least among some parts of 
society theres not only less compassion but more organized 
hostility toward the homeless said gary blasi president of the 
national coalition for the homeless and a legal aid foundation 
attorney in los angeles a city with a homeless population 
estimated at more than 150000 
a large part of the source of the hostility is that its not 
great to have a lot of homeless people around when youre a tourist 
city blasi said its not just the cable cars and the golden 
gate anymore 
what passes for heartlessness often is case of empty municipal 
pockets with compassionate programs succumbing to financial 
pressures the city council in washington faced with a 95 million 
budget deficit voted in june to gut its policy of guaranteeing 
overnight shelter to anyone who requested it that ordinance was 
championed by the late homeless activist mitch snyder and passed 
six years ago by more than 70 percent of the vote 
in philadelphia 80 members of the mayors publicprivate task 
force on homelessness resigned in july to protest massive cuts in 
the citys budget for homeless services after the amount dropped 
from 34 million to 10 million in two years at the same time the 
city plans to spend 1 million closing off spaces under train 
platforms in a downtown station where people like to sleep 
i see no abatement whatsoever in peoples concern people 
calling people coming in people of all ages making an effort and 
reaching out said phyllis ryan director of the philadelphia 
committee for the homeless and one of the former task force 
members the government resources have just not been sufficient 
i think they just looked out there and decided whos a voter and 
who isnt 
in some places voters aggravated by the homeless problem are 
using their electoral clout to protest residents in santa monica 
calif have collected thousands of signatures to place a 
proposition on the november ballot to make the city attorneys 
office an elected one the current city attorney robert myers has 
refused to prosecute people for sleeping outdoors 
i think theres an increasing feeling of helplessness said 
barbara stinchfield santa monicas community development manager 
we get proposals weekly on how to solve the homeless problem 
its frustrating its troubling its unsettling its not getting 
better but most people are not reacting in a really destructive 
way 
citizens in santa cruz calif took their anger to the streets 
when 200 homeless activists rallied outside the santa cruz county 
courthouse demanding an end to the citys camping ban they were 
outnumbered by 600 counterdemonstrators who said they were tired of 
giving bums and squatters a free ride in the seaside town 
about 75 miles south of san francisco 
i think what happened in santa cruz and san francisco has to 
do with something much bigger than homelessness gleason said 
the american public she believes feels angry but helpless over 
things like the hud scandal and the savingsandloan bailout i 
think people are feeling so frustrated from being bamboozled and 
taken advantage of on every front homelessness gets lumped in with 
the rest of it its very easy to take your anger out on the poor 
its more difficult to find effective solutions to the problem 
but citizens in seattle are trying said martha dilts executive 
director of seattle emergency housing service 
seattle residents are trying to raise 1 million for 
transitional housing for homeless families and a local real estate 
companys agents are donating part of their commissions to fight 
homelessness 
i see people starting to realize that homelessness is 
affecting more people that it could happen to your family or your 
neighbor theres a feeling of community and a sense of we can do 
it said dilts a member of the governors homeless task force 
advocates agree that homelessness will persist until society 
deals with the lack of affordable housing access to drug treatment 
and mental health facilities and absence of affordable childcare 
and other support services for the working poor meanwhile cities 
are eing forced to expand and improve shelter facilities something 
many communities are loathe to do 
although washington has been under court order to expand its 
shelter system council members say neighborhoods will not accept 
one without a fight in one area a homeless mans arrest on murder 
charges galvanized the neighbors they held bake sales to finance 
their effort to close the shelter in which he lived 
in a suburban westchester county ny community neighbors 
have filed five lawsuits to try to stop construction of a 108unit 
complex for homeless women and children in a san jose calif 
neighborhood residents are fighting a homeless shelter they 
believe is responsible for a 120 percent increase in felonies in 
their area 
if there was a shred of sympathy in me before one resident 
said after seeing this i have lost all compassion 
sometimes however neighbors find the cure far less painful 
than they had anticipated a project to help mentally ill homeless 
women in denver was welcomed into a neighborhood after residents 
fears were allayed by the projects planners the house has been a 
smashing problemfree success 78 percent of those who passed 
through there in the first year now have homes and neighbors now 
drop by to donate lawn chairs and tomato plants 
i dont think the american public knows whats going on in 
homeless services today gleason said part of it is 
misinformation part of it is honesttogod displaced anger when 
people understand both what the homeless reality is and what were 
trying to do about it it paints a whole different picture 
</TEXT>
