<TEXT>
two months after winning an 
overwhelming mandate to govern burmas democratic opposition is 
being kept out of office by a military administration that shows no 
signs of stepping aside 
the ruling state law and order restoration council has added new 
conditions that could indefinitely delay a transfer of power to the 
national league for democracy which swept the may 27 parliamentary 
election 
the scene is set for a confrontation and the feeling is now 
that unless the nld stands up to be counted the military rulers 
will prevail said a senior western diplomat reached in rangoon 
capital of burma 
the nld may have scored a major election victory but the 
military rulers are the still the ones with the guns he said 
speaking on condition of anonymity 
antigovernment street protests have increased despite 
prohibitions under martial law diplomats said demonstrations by 
young people in rangoon and mandalay to the north were the 
largest in months 
a cartoon in an exile newsletter expressed the feelings of many 
burmese a meanlooking soldier points a revolver at the face of a 
ragged civilian and snarls idiot i said id give you elections 
i didnt say id hand over power 
on july 29 more than 1000 supporters of the national league 
for democracy waited outside a rangoon conference hall where party 
officials adopted a resolution demanding parliament be convened in 
september 
other demands in the resolution included dialogue with the 
government democratic rights and the release of party leaders 
they include aung san suu kyi an outspoken critic of military rule 
who remains under house arrest although her oneyear sentence 
expired july 19 
police and soldiers surrounded the hall throughout the twoday 
meeting 
gen saw maungs government promised the election the first in 
30 years of authoritarian rule after taking power in september 
1988 his soldiers killed thousands of civilians who demonstrated 
for democracy 
western diplomats said the government probably was astonished by 
the magnitude of its loss the national league took 392 of 485 
parliamentary seats and most of the rest went to groups close to 
it 
after it came to power saw maungs government suspended the 
constitution and said the parliament to be chosen in the promised 
elections must approve a new one before power could be transferred 
on march 27 the general said political parties could follow 
their own programs after the election 
some are saying an interim government will be first formed and 
power transferred under an interim constitution and they will take 
time in drafting a constitution he said they can do what they 
want 
before the vote the government spokesmen also said the new 
parliament could adopt a constitution based on the charter of 1947 
the one that replaced it in 1974 or entirely new 
following their victory national league officials said they 
wanted to adopt the 1947 constitution temporarily and revise it 
on july 13 the powerful chief of military intelligence maj 
gen khin nyunt said the 1947 constitution no longer was 
appropriate and a totally new one was needed 
he added more conditions july 27 saying the government would 
convene a national conference to provide guidelines for drafting a 
charter which then must be approved by referendum 
drafting of an interim constitution to obtain state power will 
not be accepted in any way and if it is done effective action 
will be taken according to the law he declared 
a political organization does not automatically obtain the 
three sovereign powers of legislative administrative and judiciary 
power by the emergence of a peoples assembly he said 
the new parliaments function was merely to draw up a 
constitution he said the national league disagreed and declared 
at its conference that the parliament was not merely a constituent 
assembly 
it is against political nature that the nld which has 
overwhelmingly won enough seats to form a government itself 
has been prohibited from the minimum of democratic rights the 
declaration said it is shameful in the eyes of the people and 
the international community 
party leaders had drafted a provisional constitution that would 
be refined by the parliament the statement said 
a western diplomat said the declaration was a direct challenge 
to the military but that the national league was treading 
carefully 
resentment of military rule remains strong and widespread but 
diplomats doubt the huge demonstrations of 1988 will be repeated 
the army has constantly reminded people that it is quite 
willing to take the same action as it did in 1988 one said 
 
