<TEXT>
the oil war between iraq and kuwait 
jeopardizes an important lifeline for the world economy and 
americans already are seeing the results at the gasoline pump 
here are some questions and answers to help explain the economic 
stakes in the gulf crisis 
q cant we get by without iraqs oil 
a yes and apparently we will since president bush has ordered 
a total cutoff of imports from iraq the united states japan 
canada and the european community announced embargoes on iraqi oil 
after iraqs invasion thursday of kuwait 
q if we dont need iraqs oil why would prices go up 
a often the price of oil is influenced more by fear than logic 
if oil companies and brokers decide theres a chance that the 
persian gulf crisis could worsen they are likely to bid for the 
first available barrel rather than use one already in storage the 
more the bidding the higher the price goes some critics say the 
oil companies take advantage of this uncertainty by jacking up 
their prices at the gasoline pump although the industry hotly 
disputes this 
q does this mean ill be paying more at the pump 
a almost surely the american automobile association says its 
survey of gasoline stations showed prices rose by 4 to 14 cents a 
gallon in just the first two days after the iraqi invasion edward 
rothschild of citizen action a washingtonbased consumer group 
thinks prices will jump 15 to 20 cents a gallon by the end of the 
month but the bush administration says it sees no risk of a big 
rise 
q wouldnt it help if american oil companies pumped more crude 
a probably but theres no chance of that in fact its the 
lack of spare production capacity in part that makes the us 
consumer vulnerable to price increases caused by foreign wars us 
oil companies have been shutting down wells since 1986 when a 
collapse of crude prices made many smaller wells uneconomic 
domestic oil production is down 20 percent since 1985 and the 
number of oil and natural gas operators in this country has plunged 
from 13000 to 4500 since 1985 according to the independent 
petroleum association of america a trade group 
q if more oil supply is the answer to keeping down prices why 
is bush boycotting iraq 
a the embargo is mainly a diplomatic tool the president 
himself said friday he couldnt assure the american public that the 
pressure tactic would pay off in fact the administration may not 
be anxious for it to work too well if every nation refused to buy 
iraqs oil the world would suddenly find itself short of oil at 
least for a short time 
if we were truly successful on the embargo we would throw 
ourselves into a serious recession said rep philip r sharp 
dind chairman of the house energy and commerce subcommittee on 
energy and power 
q doesnt the united states have emergency oil reserved for 
crises like this 
a yes there is a large reserve but no it apparently wont be 
used under the current circumstances known as the strategic 
petroleum reserve the system is a series of salt caverns in 
louisiana and texas that holds nearly 590 million barrels of oil 
or enough to replace more than onethird of us imports for 170 
days 
the reserve which was started in 1975 in response to the 1973 
arab oil embargo has never been used and the administration says 
it sees no need for tapping it now 
