<TEXT>
here are some facts and figures on liberia 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the land the west african nation is bordered by ivory coast 
guinea and sierra leone and covers 42900 square miles about the 
size of ohio the coastal plain gives way to rocky cliffs and 
strong tides make access to the atlantic ocean difficult the 
highest elevations are in the northern highlands which rise up to 
4500 feet the capital is monrovia 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the people the population is estimated at about 25 million 
including 16 principal tribal groups and about 50000 descendants 
of freed american slaves who founded the country english is the 
official language the vast majority of the country practices 
traditional african religions 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the economy even before the rebel insurgency began the economy 
was near collapse although liberia possesses some of the richest 
iron ore in the world the country has been unable to pay its 
foreign debt and it has been suspended by the international 
monetary fund mining has earned more than 64 percent of liberias 
foreign exchange but agriculture has remained the main employer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the history in 1822 freed american slaves visited liberia and 
began settlements they declared liberia an independent republic in 
1847 descendants of the freed slaves called americoliberians 
dominated the country until thenmaster sgt samuel k doe led a 
military coup on april 12 1979 he was popular with the majority 
of liberians who resented the dominance of the americoliberians 
doe headed a military government until october 1985 when elections 
were held he claimed victory but opposition parties and 
independent observers said the vote was rigged on dec 24 1989 
former doe aide charles taylor invaded with a small band of men 
from ivory coast taylor said he intended to topple does 
government another rebel leader prince johnson split with taylor 
and now controls much of monrovia 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900806-0025 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
december 24 two groups of rebels led by charles taylor cross 
the border from the ivory coast one attacks a customs station in 
eastern nimba county and the other heads toward the capital of 
monrovia 
january 3 president samuel k doe fires his internal affairs 
minister col edward sackor and stephen daniels superintendent 
of nimba county for mishandling reports of the rebel invasion 
january 5 fighting between liberian forces and rebels opposed 
to doe destroys two towns in northeastern liberia and sends 
thousands fleeing across the border 
may 7 doe calls for negotiations with rebel forces on ending 
their fourmonth insurgency 
may 29 doe asks the legislature to call early elections after 
rebel forces move within 35 miles of the capital and take control 
of most of the countrys major economic enterprises 
june 1 doe announces he will not run for reelection and asks 
the united states and other nations to help end the civil war 
june 5 state department officials say the american military 
has no role to play in liberias internal conflict even though 
more than 2000 marines are poised offshore to help evacuate us 
citizens from the african nation 
june 8 the government says it is willing to accept a 
ceasefire and begin negotiating with a rebel army 
june 10 rebels win control of liberias international airport 
june 12 a delegation of liberian rebels arrives for talks with 
government officials aimed at ending the fighting 
june 16 the liberian government proposes a 30day ceasefire 
june 25 liberian rebels break off peace talks with the 
government announce plans to attack monrovia 
july 7 liberias shattered government announces ceasefire on 
a makeshift radio station and appeals to shops to open and 
government workers to return to their offices 
july 12 peace talks begin in sierra leone 
july 19 foreign minister j rudolph johnson and other 
prominent liberians appeal to the united states for a temporary 
us peacekeeping force to help prevent further bloodshed 
july 21 doe expels the us military attache a government 
communique accuses the head of the us mission col david staley 
of providing support to the rebels and urging government forces to 
defect 
july 23 in a surprise attack fighters from a splinter rebel 
group led by prince johnson wade across a swamp to shoot their way 
into the capitals center 
july 30 government troops kill up to 600 people sheltered in a 
refugee compound in monrovia 
saturday johnson says he is ordering the arrest of all 
foreigners in monrovia beginning today in hope of provoking foreign 
intervention 
sunday us marines rescue 59 americans from the us embassy 
compound without firing shots or encountering resistance rebel 
leader taylor calls on civilians and soldiers to mobilize asking 
all liberians to defend their country and oppose foreign 
intervention 
