<TEXT>
three years ago prime minister yasuhiro nakasone 
conceded it was only too true to say that japan was getting a 
free ride through the turmoil of warfare in the persian gulf 
now nakasone is out of office and the iraniraq war has been 
supplanted by the iraqi seizure of kuwait 
japan for a change is showing itself willing to take a hit in 
the pocketbook as the price of taking a stand against iraqi 
president saddam husseins aggression in the worlds biggest 
oilproducing region 
the sanctions announced sunday are the toughest this country has 
imposed fallout from them will affect daily life in japan prime 
minister toshiki kaifu said today 
financial markets reacted by selling the yen and driving down 
japanese stocks in anticipation of real economic costs in increased 
oil prices and inflationary pressure 
as a country that imports 99 percent of its oil including 70 
percent from the middle east japan has until now been extremely 
cautious in its middle east policy but the strong sanctions 
announced sunday night show tokyo moving toward the global 
partnership with the united states and western europe that 
washington has encouraged 
japan said it will ban imports of oil from iraq and kuwait and 
all japanese exports to the two nations it also will freeze 
economic aid and loans to iraq and suspend investment financing 
and other capital flows to iraq and kuwait 
for much of the weekend it had appeared japans only reaction 
would be its issuing friday of administrative guidance to banks and 
financial institutions to freeze kuwaiti assets in japan estimated 
at 20 billion 
the hesitance shows how hard it is to break the habit of basing 
foreign policy on domestic economic considerations 
japanese news reports said the foreign ministry had been urging 
the government to join us and european sanctions while the 
ministry of international trade and industry argued that sanctions 
would badly hurt the japanese economy 
sanctions easier said than done said a headline in 
sundays mainichi daily news on an article noting that sanctions 
would stop iaqs repayments on 46 billion worth of japanese loans 
in the end us pressure helped tip the balance president bush 
telephoned kaifu on saturday urging tokyo to join tough sanctions 
and all 100 members of the us senate urged japan to take 
mandatory and comprehensive sanctions against iraq 
growing more than 4 percent annually in recent years the 
japanese economy is less reliant on oil than it was during the 
197374 oil shock when the arab oil embargo knocked japan into 
a recession then oil provided 78 percent of japans energy needs 
as opposed to 57 percent now 
japan received 62 percent of its oil from iraq in the first 
quarter of 1990 importing an average of 260000 barrels a day it 
obtained 5 percent of its oil from kuwait or 210000 barrels a 
day according to the trade ministry 
japanese companies were criticized for buying up iranian oil in 
1979 during the usiran dispute and later when tankers were 
attacked by both sides in the iraniraq war it came under fire for 
not doing more to help freedom of navigation in the persian gulf 
nakasone who tried to lead japan into a more worldoriented 
posture during his 198287 tenure as prime minister said in 1987 
that japan would be isolated if it didnt aid in the international 
effort to let oil flow out of the persian gulf to japan and other 
nations 
japan subsequently paid for a 10 million navigation system to 
monitor ship movements in the gulf and made a generous package of 
loans to jordan and other prowestern countries to try to promote 
stability in the middle east 
those measures and a more evenhanded policy toward israel were 
touted as steps toward a more active japanese policy in the region 
earlier this year japan offered 195 billion in economic aid 
to poland and hungary flexing its wealth in another region where 
like the middle east japan had kept a low profile 
the surprisingly strong sanctions announced against baghdad show 
another area where japan is willing to forge a new policy despite 
economic risk 
</TEXT>
