<TEXT>
a quarter of the 40000 infant deaths that occur 
in the united states each year could be easily prevented with 
existing medical knowledge according to a highlevel bush 
administration study 
the new york times reported today that the study calls for 
spending about 500 million a year more to reduce the countrys 
infant mortality rate ninteen other countries have lower rates 
the report was begun in july 1989 by a group headed by assistant 
secretary of health and human services james o mason but appears 
to have been put on hold the times said 
the report found that common techniques including improved 
prenatal care could also prevent vision and hearing loss mental 
retardation and other handicaps that afflict 100000 newborns each 
year 
the united states has not achieved its national goals for 
reducing infant mortality the study said unacceptable racial 
disparities and significant geographic inequities are still 
evident and progress in reducing the rate of infant mortality has 
slowed significantly especially among blacks 
the times said it obtained a copy of the report from an official 
involved in the study who felt its recommendations were being 
ignored others involved in the study said it had been shelved 
