<TEXT>
kuwaits oil export facilities are shut 
down and will remain so for some time and there is considerable 
doubt saudi arabia will be willing to make up the potential world 
oil shortage the middle east economic survey said today 
the weekly newsletter published in nicosia said the total loss 
of supply to world oil markets because of the kuwaiti shutdown and 
embargoes on iraqi oil could exceed 4 million barrels a day 
there will be a potential restriction of oil supply in the 
near future that could range in intensity from significant to 
highly severe depending on how circumstances unfold it wrote 
the respected newletter said kuwaiti oil production and exports 
cut after iraqi president saddam husseins powerful army invaded 
on thursday would be shut down for some time both for 
physicaltechnical reasons and as a consequence of impending 
international efforts to interdict purchases of kuwaiti oil 
the newsletter said the impact of the kuwaiti shutdown could be 
compounded by restrictions on iraqi oil supplies 
since friday when the article was written numerous sanctions 
have been announced including japanese and european embargoes on 
iraqi and kuwaiti oil the united states announced an on thursday 
just hours after iraq invaded its oilrich neighbor 
as a result of the embargos iraq today closed one of two major 
pipelines that was pumping its oil through turkey to a terminal on 
the mediterranean it said the second pipeline would be used at 
just 70 percent capacity 
the pipelines were carrying about 15 million barrels of oil a 
day more than half iraqs daily output 
if anything like the full iraqikuwaiti shortfall of 4 million 
barrels a day manifests itself the world will not be able to get 
by for very long without some additional supply from other sources 
above and beyond the current opec quota levels the newsletter 
said 
it said current spare capacity by members of the organization of 
petroleum exporting countries amounted to not much more than 35 
million barrels of oil a day 
this spare capacity is concentrated in a few countries saudi 
arabia with a spare 2 million barrels a day the united arab 
emirates with 600000 venezuela with 500000 and libya with 
300000 the newsletter said 
here the key obviously lies with saudi arabia and there must 
be considerable doubt as to how far the kingdom would be prepared 
to go on antagonizing iraq by cooperating with measures to restrict 
iraqi oil exports and increase its own production in deference to 
the wishes of the united states and the world community it said 
iraq and kuwait have accounted for 20 percent of opecs output 
the newsletter noted that iraqs preinvasion oil exports 
amounted to 27 to 28 million barrels a day divided between three 
outlets pipelines across saudi arabia and turkey and the gulf sea 
lanes 
it said 15 million barrels a day were exported using the 
pipeline through turkey to the mediterranean 900000 via the saudi 
arabian pipeline to the red sea and 300000 to 400000 loaded onto 
tankers at iraqs mina albakr terminal in the northern persian 
gulf 
