<TEXT>
the food and drug administration today 
approved a drug that could help save thousands of premature infants 
born with immature lungs 
the drug a powder mixed with sterile water substitutes for a 
naturally occurring foam that coats the inside of the lungs and 
keeps them from collapsing when the infant exhales 
the infants receive the drug through a tube into their 
windpipes they must be on a mechanical ventilator to receive it 
about 250000 infants are born prematurely each year in the 
united states onefifth of them have respiratory distress 
syndrome or breathing difficulties due to immature lungs the 
problem is fatal in some 5000 cases a year 
that makes respiratory distress syndrome the leading cause of 
death and disability among premature infants the fda said in 
1963 a baby born to president kennedy and his wife died of the 
condition 
the newly approved drug called exosurf neonatal can be used 
immediately after birth to prevent death in highrisk infants under 
three pounds and also to treat infants who have developed the 
disease 
the fda said the drug represents such an important advance that 
it has been widely available since july 1989 when it was still 
experimental 
the drug was invented by dr john clements of the university of 
california at san francisco burroughs wellcome co of research 
triangle park nc applied to market it in february the fda said 
its approval came in a nearrecord five months 
the fda also said it has designated exosurf an orphan drug under 
a program that provides incentives for the development and 
production of drugs and medical products to treat conditions 
affecting small numbers of people 
</TEXT>
