<TEXT>
 
here are some facts and figures on kuwait 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
land kuwait a land of 6880 square miles is bordered by iraq 
to the north and west saudi arabia to the southsouthwest and the 
persian gulf to the east the oilrich country is flat and very 
dry the nation gets an average of 5 inches of rain a year 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
people about onequarter of kuwaits 17 million residents 
live in the capital of kuwait city and its suburbs more than half 
are foreigners mainly arabs including 300000 palestinians most 
kuwaitis are sunni moslem but 30 percent adhere to the rival 
shiite sect shiites of iranian descent number nearly 150000 the 
alsabah clan has ruled kuwait as an emirate since they settled 
there in 1756 after trekking from the arabian hinterland more than 
70 percent of the people speak arabic the official language while 
10 percent speak kurdish and 4 percent persian a constitutional 
monarchy rules the country 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
economy oil is the chief resource of kuwait a member of the 
organization of petroleum exporting countries only 1 percent of 
the land is cultivated per capita income in 1986 was 13890 oil 
revenue reached 30 billion in 1983 but has been declining since 
because of a drop in oil prices and production curbs kuwait 
currently produces about 15 million barrels of oil a day and has 
reserves of 897 billion barrels 128 percent of world reserves 
and enough to last for more than 250 years little grows in the 
desert climate so the emirate has to import nearly all its food 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
history the mongols arab caliphs and ottomans were in turn 
overlords of the bleak and largely unpopulated land until 1899 
when the british became the dominant power in the region kuwait 
gained its independence in 1961 it is a member of the sixnation 
gulf cooperation council a defense and economic alliance iraq 
which has historically laid claim to all of kuwait invaded 
thursday and announced the formation of a provisional government 
the alsabah family fled to saudi arabia 
</TEXT>
