<TEXT>
hiroshima on monday mourned the 140000 
victims of the 1945 atomic bomb attack with a solemn look back and 
a note of optimism for the future as tensions ease between the 
soviet union and the united states 
for an eery moment the city fell silent taxis and street cars 
stopped and people throughout this industrial center of 1 million 
joined in a moment of prayer for the souls of those killed in the 
bombing 
dignitaries hiroshima residents and foreign guests bowed their 
heads at 815 am the exact moment the bomb exploded in a 
blinding flash of light 
i pay my deep respects to the citizens of hiroshima who have 
built this city of international peace from the ashes prime 
minister toshiki kaifu said at a ceremony attended by 55000 people 
as the only country in the world to have experienced an atom 
bomb attack japan has resolved not to let it be repeated kaifu 
said he reiterated japans appeals for total nuclear disarmament 
kaifu told a news conference that his government was working to 
increase medical and financial support for those exposed to the 
bombs radiation 
hiroshima mayor takeshi araki in his annual peace declaration 
praised the growing promises for disarmament in the united states 
and the soviet union 
hiroshima has the highest regard for this tide of disarmament 
changing the fate of mankind from one of annihilation to one of 
survival araki said 
the united states in an effort to avoid a bloody invasion of 
japan to end world war ii dropped an atomic bomb on hiroshima on 
aug 6 1945 it wiped out nearly half the citys population 
killing most immediately many others died within a few months 
mostly from radiation or burns 
hiroshima a major military center during the war has been 
honoring the dead at a solemn peace ceremony annually for 43 years 
but not all hiroshima residents can face the memories retired 
school teacher minako tanabe said her husband has never attended 
the ceremony although he has lived in hiroshima all his life 
my husband wont come here because its too sad so many of 
his friends died that day ms tanabe said 
monday thousands of visitors streamed through the citys peace 
memorial park leaving flowers messages and garlands of folded 
paper cranes symbols of peace draped around the parks 29 
monuments 
at a ceremony officials added 5551 names of people exposed to 
the bomb who died over the past year to the names enshrined in a 
granite cenotaph raising the total of claimed victims to 167243 
but it is difficult to determine which deaths were directly 
related to the bomb and 140000 victims is the more accepted 
figure many researchers believe the risk of death from leukemia 
lung bone and breast cancer is greater for those exposed to the 
bomb 
three days after the attack on hiroshima the united states 
dropped a second atom bomb on the city of nagasaki killing 70000 
civilians japan surrendered six days later ending world war ii 
</TEXT>
