<TEXT>
republican gov mike hayden has never lost 
since he first won election to the kansas house of representatives 
in 1972 but he faces a strong challenge from a political newcomer 
in tuesdays primary election 
recent polls have had wichita real estate executive nestor 
weigand jr gaining rapidly on hayden in a sixway battle for the 
gop governor nomination 
one poll last week put weigand ahead but by such a small margin 
that the race was considered too close to call hayden claimed his 
own polling had him solidly ahead 
on the democratic side former gov john carlin who served in 
197987 and was ineligible under the state constitution to run for 
a third fouryear term in 1986 was expected to have less trouble 
than hayden in winning his partys nomination 
carlins chief rival for the democratic nomination is joan 
finney who has been state treasurer for 15 years 
the problems for hayden 46 stem from a lack of popularity in 
urban areas and the political backlash from property taxes that 
soared after the state reappraised all property and implemented a 
classification system that assessed property at different rates 
the changes hit some medium and small businesses especially hard 
and taxpayer protest groups came to the capitol last winter 
demanding changes when the legislature adjourned in early may 
without doing anything hayden bore the brunt of the blame 
weigand 51 wealthy president of a family real estate business 
the largest in wichita has tried to capitalize on the discontent 
billing himself as a candidate who can solve the property tax 
problem 
however weigand has been criticized for lacking governmental 
knowledge and for proposing impractical solutions such as 
restoring business inventories to the tax rolls which industry 
strongly opposes and probably can block in the legislature 
also at stake on tuesdays ballot were nominations for one us 
senate seat and five seats in the house 
us sen nancy kassebaum faced token opposition in the 
republican senatorial primary from littleknown gregory walstrom of 
lawrence 
in the democratic primary for kassebaums seat former us rep 
bill roy filed for nomination in june than a week later announced 
he would not campaign for it roy represented northeast kansas in 
congress in 197175 and lost senatorial races to bob dole in 1974 
and to kassebaum in 1978 
roy could not get his name off the ballot after the filing 
deadline and could beat political neophyte dick williams on name 
recognition alone if so roy will have to decide if he wants to 
campaign against kassebaum in the fall 
on the house side us rep bob whittaker who has represented 
southeast kansas in washington for 12 years did not seek 
reelection this year and 10 candidates sought the two party 
nominations to succeed him there was no clearcut favorite in 
either party 
incumbent republican reps pat roberts and jan meyers and 
democrat dan glickman had no primary opposition while democrat jim 
slattery faced token opposition in mark creamer a crusader for the 
legalization of marijuana who sat in jail on a possession 
conviction during the primary campaign 
secretary of state bill graves forecast a turnout of 415000 
voters 275000 in the republican primary and 140000 in the 
democratic primary kansas has 1166 million registered voters but 
346000 of them are not registered with either party 
