the world health organization on monday urged a 
smoking ban on all passenger aircraft 
we are now calling for all airlines to be smokefree we think 
its sensible we think its possible and we think the airlines 
would support it john roberts whos tobacco and health program 
manager told reporters 
martin jarvis senior scientist of the imperial cancer research 
fund said separately simply having nonsmoking seats on 
aircraft is not an answer to the problem nonsmokers are still 
exposed to smoke 
air canada last month became the first airline to ban smoking on 
all its transatlantic flights smoking is banned on most domestic 
flights in the united states 
a survey conducted by the world health organization and the 
british medical association found that some airlines would welcome 
a smoking ban if it was introduced by a third party such as a 
government or aviation industry body 
the survey showed the main reason airlines changed their smoking 
policy was pressure from consumers 
you cant step off an aircraft if you dont like the smoke 
you are trapped roberts said 
a prosmoking group forest attacked the survey saying yet 
again the bma forget that the role of doctors is to serve their 
patients not to dictate to them by force of law how they should 
live their lives 
