<TEXT>
the productivity of american workers improved 
for the first time in 18 months climbing at an annual rate of 16 
percent the government said monday 
analysts said they were encouraged by the gain in nonfarm 
productivity defined as output per hour of work especially in 
light of recent data showing rising unemployment and stagnant 
economic growth 
its one tiny bright spot in the midst of a lot of 
negatives said david jones an economist with aubrey g lanston 
amp co a government securities dealer in new york 
however economists said the 16 percent gain was still below 
the level needed to dramatically boost americans standard of 
living and improve the nations ability to compete internationally 
they also were disturbed at the reports findings on hourly 
labor costs a major inflation measure for businesses those costs 
rose at an annual rate of 56 percent the second quarter of 1990 
well above the 3 percent rise for all of 1989 
the inflation numbers for the rest of the year look horrible 
especially with the shock of the middle east oil crisis said 
michael k evans who heads a washington economic forecasting firm 
the rise in productivity in the second three months of the year 
was the first increase since productivity climbed 05 percent in 
the final quarter of 1988 the labor department said 
though the report offered good news on american workers 
performance in the apriljune period the agency said revised 
figures on last year showed productivity actually fell 03 percent 
rather than increasing 09 percent as first reported 
the poor 1989 showing was the worst since nonfarm productivity 
dropped 09 percent during the 198182 recession the government 
said 
the report showed that from april to june the number of hours 
americans worked fell 01 percent a likely sign that workers were 
being laid off in the face of slower economic growth and businesses 
just werent hiring as many new workers analysts said 
its a good newsbad news thing evans said the good news 
is that producers are starting to cut costs and lay off 
inefficient workers and the bad news is that when they lay off 
too many workers we have a recession 
in revising numbers for the first quarter of 1990 the agency 
offered slightly better figures saying productivity fell 19 
percent rather than the 27 percent plunge first reported 
mondays report showed that unit labor costs a key gauge of 
future price inflation rose 39 percent for the apriljune period 
compared with a 33 percent increase during all of 1989 
in the manufacturing sector productivity increased 37 percent 
a big improvement over the 2 percent increase during all of 1989 
unit labor costs in that sector rose 26 percent compared with the 
22 percent increase during all of last year 
total business productivity including farming rose 19 percent 
for the first quarter compared with a 02 percent drop for all of 
1989 
since 1982 productivity growth has averaged 14 percent a year 
increasing productivity is considered basic to boosting living 
standards because it allows businesses to pay workers more as their 
output rises without risking higher inflation 
</TEXT>
