the grim business of fighting crime will 
lighten up a little tuesday when millions of people are expected to 
join in the seventh annual national night out 
the event started with the suggestion that for one night 
people turn on their exterior lights and go outside as a presence 
against street crime 
more people join in every year and they find novel ways to make 
a statement said matt peskin national coordinator from this 
philadelphia suburb 
its a july 4 atmosphere but theres seriousness said 
peskin we call it a party with a purpose 
cities will sponsor hundreds of block parties for residents and 
police milwaukee is planning 1000 of them plus demonstrations to 
show people how they can illuminate their properties 
night outers in syracuse ny will hold a candlelight march 
organizers in cedar rapids iowa will hand out lollipops wrapped 
in the local theme light it bright lock it tight lick crime 
in louisville ky fire sirens and church bells will sound at 8 
pm a signal for people to turn on their outside lights and check 
the batteries in their home smoke detectors 
the first year we had about 2 million people in 400 
communities in 23 states peskin said after the second and 
third ones things began to pick up last year we counted 202 
million people participating in 7620 communities 
this year the night out organizers hope more than 21 million 
people will turn out in 8000 communities in all 50 states plus 
canadian cities and on us military bases around the world 
there have been a few success stories night out people who 
spotted a breakin and notified police peskin said and so far no 
confrontations or incidents of retaliation 
generally speaking crimewise its pretty quiet that night 
peskin said houston measured it last year and they were down 51 
percent in major crimes for that full day 
