<TEXT>
disruption of oil supplies from iraq and kuwait 
poses no immediate danger of shortages experts said monday 
but the worlds oil reserves could be called upon quickly 
putting upward pressure on prices they said 
all eyes will be on saudi arabia which has the greatest 
capacity to make up for the disruption but would fear retaliation 
from neighboring iraq the experts said 
in the shortterm i dont think people are panicking too 
much said lucy mullins an oil analyst at the london investment 
firm of barclays de zoete wedd ltd the world could last six 
months or so almost quite happily 
the iraqi supply is being disrupted by a joint embargo by the 
united states the european community and japan iraq on monday 
reduced the flow of oil through turkish pipelines which can carry 
up to half of iraqs oil production 
kuwaiti production has come to a halt since iraqs thursday 
morning invasion 
although iraq and kuwait are among the worlds biggest 
producers their combined production of 47 million barrels a day 
represents just 9 percent of the worlds output 
the oil market has been experiencing an excess of supply and oil 
importers stocks are high experts say the oil shocks of the 
1970s also have made industrial nations used to cutting demand 
oil prices still jumped about 3 a barrel monday as oil buyers 
scurried to secure supplies the spot price of north sea brent 
blend the most widely traded international crude oil was trading 
at 2629 a barrel in london late monday afternoon 
the 24nation international energy agencys governing board 
planned to meet at its paris headquarters on thursday to assess the 
situations impact on its members spokeswoman joyce heard said 
but the meeting was unlikely to result in the imposition of the 
agencys emergency oil sharing program she said 
one or more member countries must be deprived of at least 7 
percent of its normal oil supply before the countries start sharing 
their oil she said 
but the board was expected to discuss demand restraint measures 
which can include taxes fuel switching and the use of oil stocks 
she said 
iraq produced 31 million barrels a day in july and kuwait 16 
million the iea said 
total world production came to 542 million barrels a day in the 
second quarter the agency said 
consumption in the traditionally weak threemonth summer period 
came to 514 million barrels a day 
as of july the 24nation organization for economic cooperation 
and development had 99 days worth of oil stocks the iea said 
the middle east economic survey a weekly newsletter reported 
monday that current excess capacity by members of the organization 
of petroleum exporting countries amounted to 35 million barrels of 
oil a day 
this extra capacity is concentrated in saudi arabia with a spare 
2 million barrels a day the united arab emirates with 600000 
venezuela with 500000 and libya with 300000 the newsletter said 
venezuela far from iraq is most likely to increase its output 
experts said norway which doesnt belong to opec might be able 
to kick in an extra 200000 barrels a day ms mullins said 
but supplies from the north sea have been constrained by summer 
maintenance and industrial action by oil workers 
it is still unknown if opec members will observe their output 
quotas and back the oil shortage 
some members would welcome the higher prices prompted by iraqs 
actions but pricing moderates in the cartel might increase output 
to ease prices and reduce the crises 
said ian graham an oil analyst with county natwest woodmac 
its a matter of whether saudi arabia feels confident enough to 
bump up its production in the face of a belligerent neighbor 
