<TEXT>
the us food and drug administration said 
monday it has approved a drug that cuts the death rate in half in 
premature infants suffering from a severe lung disease 
the disease called respiratory distress syndrome is the most 
common cause of death in infants under 30 days old the american 
lung association said the ailment afflicts 50000 infants each 
year and kills about 3000 of them the lung association said 
the drug called exosurf is a mixture of synthetic chemicals 
that mimic the action of lung surfactant a liquid found in the 
lungs that helps keep them inflated premature infants are unable 
to make surfactant and their lungs can collapse if not treated 
the drug was invented by dr john clements of the university of 
california san francisco and is made by burroughs wellcome co of 
research triangle park nc 
the approval of the drug is a very important development 
said dr mary ellen avery professor of pediatrics at harvard 
medical school in boston there has been a significant reduction 
in deaths among those who were treated 
exosurf and another experimental surfactant made from cows 
lungs have both been available since last year when the fda 
allowed distribution under what is called a treatment ind that 
is intended to make lifesaving experimental drugs available before 
approval 
the bovine surfactant called survanta is made by abbott 
laboratories in abbott park ill 
both have been widely used and although they have not been 
directly compared both work pretty well said avery who has 
used them i dont think anyone is in a position to say which is 
better 
a spokesman for abbott said approval of survanta was expected 
soon 
dr anthony corbet a neonatologist at the baylor college of 
medicine in houston who has participated in experimental studies of 
exosurf said this drug will have its greatest place in treating 
very small premature infants perhaps those under 3 pounds but 
those babies under 3 pounds make a very large contribution to 
infant mortality 
the infant mortality rate in the united states is 10 deaths per 
1000 live births corbet said about three infant deaths per 1000 
are due to respiratory distress syndrome he said cutting the 
number of those deaths in half with exosurf could significantly 
lower the us infant mortality rate he said 
in studies with 1600 infants with respiratory distress 
syndrome exosurf cut the death rate by 66 percent the company 
said when given to 1800 infants who were at risk of developing 
the disease but had not yet contracted it the drug reduced the 
death rate by 50 percent company officials said 
corbet said he is giving exosurf routinely to premature newborn 
infants weighing 3 pounds or less whether they have the disease 
yet or not they have about a 70 percent chance of developing the 
disease he said 
in less premature infants corbet said he generally administers 
the drug when the disease appears 
dr richard kent of burroughs wellcome explained that in the 
absence of surfactant the little air sacs in the lung called 
alveoli collapse like inflated balloons if air pressure is not 
maintained when surfactant is added the alveoli become more like 
bubblegum bubbles and maintain their shape when air pressure 
falls he said 
about 10000 infants have been treated with the drug so far 
kent said infants getting the drug in the clinical trials showed 
few side effects with the exception of apnea a treatable disorder 
in which infants intermittently stop breathing for short periods 
the company said there was also a slight increase in bleeding in 
the lungs the company said 
corbet said the drug reduces the need for oxygen and ventilators 
with premature infants and thus can reduce lung injury 
both oxygen and the pressure from the ventilator damage the 
lungs he said and you get lung injury which doesnt go away 
very quickly that causes a great lengthening of hospitalization 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900806-0097 </DOCNO>
