<TEXT>
the widening income gap between the rich and 
the poor in the united states has hit hispanics especially hard a 
research group said monday 
hispanics have traditionally earned less than nonhispanics but 
a study by the center on budget and policy priorities said the 
difference grew in the 1980s because hispanic income stagnated 
wage levels declined and there were fewer government assistance 
programs to aid the poor the center said 
in 1979 the group said the income of the typical hispanic 
family was 71 percent that of the average nonhispanic family that 
figure had fallen to 66 percent by 1988 
the center found 28 percent of hispanics had incomes placing 
them in the poorest onefifth of households in 1987 eleven percent 
of hispanic households had incomes that put them in the wealthiest 
onefifth that year 
the report came two weeks after the center reported a postworld 
war ii high in the earnings gap between poor and rich americans 
the top 20 percent of households will receive as much aftertax 
income this year as the other 80 percent combined the center said 
the center on budget and policy priorities is a nonprofit 
research organization financed by foundations that studies 
government spending programs and policies affecting low and 
moderateincome americans 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

