<TEXT>
the un security council on monday 
imposed broad sanctions against iraq for invading kuwait including 
a ban on trade aimed at cutting off the middle eastern nations oil 
trade and arms supplies 
the 15member council voted 130 to adopt a uscrafted 
resolution calling for the measures in an effort to force iraq to 
unconditionally withdraw its troops from kuwait yemen the 
councils only arab member and cuba abstained 
the resolution which was sponsored by 10 council members said 
the security council is determined to bring the invasion and 
occupation of kuwait by iraq to an end and to restore the 
sovereignty independence and territorial integrity of kuwait 
the measure which takes effect immediately bans all imports 
from iraq and kuwait it also prohibits any activities including 
the transfer of funds that would help iraq and kuwait export their 
goods and forbids loans to the two countries 
if successfully enforced the sanctions could cripple the 
oildependent iraqi economy its sweeping provisions would in 
effect bar un members from importing iraqi oil and oblige turkey 
and saudi arabia to shut down iraqi oil pipelines running through 
their territory 
the iraqis fast losing customers for their oil stopped pumping 
petroleum on monday through one of their two pipelines that run 
through turkey to the mediterranean they reduced the flow in a 
second pipeline there 
turkish president turgut ozal in an interview with abc news 
had indicated that turkey would close down the pipeline completely 
once the security council adopted the sanctions resolution we 
will obey the un embargo ozal said 
the resolution also bans the sale or supply of any commodities 
or products to iraq and kuwait which would include weapons and 
military supplies 
the only exceptions to the trade embargo under the resolution 
were for such items as food and medical supplies in special 
humanitarian circumstances 
president bush praised the councils decision and called for 
full and total implementation of these sanctions ruling out 
nothing at all 
he told reporters at the white house these sanctions must be 
enforced 
it was only the third time in its 45year existence that the 
world body had voted sanctions against a member state in 1967 the 
security council voted similar comprehensive sanctions against the 
white minority government of rhodesia a mandatory un arms 
embargo against south africa approved in 1977 is still in effect 
the sanctions are legally binding on all un members although 
past council resolutions have often been ignored or flouted the 
united nations has no enforcement mechanism but later could call on 
members to take military action against iraq or impose a blockade 
british prime minister margaret thatcher speaking to reporters 
at andrews air force base outside washington said britain and its 
allies will consider a naval blockade of iraq if the un sanctions 
prove ineffective 
the vote followed similar sanctions imposed on iraq by much of 
the west including the united states japan and the european 
community the soviet union and china said they would halt arms 
shipments to iraq 
at mondays council session us ambassador thomas pickering 
accused iraqi president saddam hussein of plunging into crisis 
the strategically critical area of the persian gulf 
iraq must learn that its disregard for international law will 
have crippling political and economic costs including but not 
limited to arms cutoffs pickering said 
iraqi ambassador abdul alanbari denounced the sanctions and 
accused the united states of pressuring other countries to take 
action against iraq 
one superpower is trying to use the un and the security 
council to realize its objectives as if the security council was 
simply its foreign ministry he said 
the iraqi ambassador said the sanctions resolution would only 
exacerbate the crisis and impede iraqi troop withdrawals from 
kuwait which baghdad says have already begun the united states 
has disputed iraqs claims about the troop withdrawal 
before the vote kuwaits ambassador mohammad abulhasan called 
the invasion a threat to international security and said strong 
un action was needed to protect small nations against aggression 
you are representing the conscience of the world he told 
the council now it is your responsibility by proving to the 
whole world that the security of nations be it big ones or small 
is not a commodity for sale or for terrorism or for threats 
security council members had been discussing possible sanctions 
for days after passing a resolution condemning iraq on thursday 
just hours after iraqi troops moved into kuwait 
the council includes the five permanent members with veto power 
the united states soviet union china britain and france the 10 
nonpermanent members are canada colombia cuba ethiopia 
finland ivory coast malaysia romania yemen and zaire 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

