<TEXT>
a mausoleum wall in one of the citys old 
cemeteries collapsed under the battering of a violent storm 
scattering bricks and the contents of dozens of tombs across a 
garden district sidewalk 
the storm sunday night knocked out a 30foot stretch of the 
plastered wall in lafayette cemetery no 1 across the street from 
commanders palace one of new orleans premier restaurants 
a clutter of bricks skulls bones and coffins pieces cascaded 
10 to 15 feet into the street said bret clesi of save our 
cemeteries a volunteer group that gives tours to raise money to 
restore new orlean cemeteries 
fortunately the wall vaults really havent been used in years 
and years and years clesi said monday 
i would be surprised if theres been a burial in those wall 
vaults in 50 years he said the size is different than modern 
caskets and many were not owned to begin with the cemetery was 
almost deserted by the 1950s 
the cemetery a cityowned owned national historic landmark was 
opened in the early 1850s only three standing graveyards are 
older and all are owned by the archdiocese of new orleans clesi 
said 
the wall contains a honeycomb of about 1000 vaults roughly big 
enough to slide a coffin into about 50 of the tombs were exposed 
by the collapse new orleans which is below sea level buries its 
dead above ground 
most of the vaults in the wall were used in the 19th century as 
temporary rental space until a family tomb could be built or 
opened clesi said 
there was a sort of rule that tombs could not be opened within 
a year and a day after the last burial he said so if someone 
in a family died six months after a funeral the family could rent 
one of these vaults and use it as a receiving vehicle until the 
tomb could be opened 
city officials attributed the damage to lightning but clesi 
said he believed the wall was buckling before the storm pounded new 
orleans with rain and hail knocked down tree branches around the 
city and battered the air with nonstop thunder and lightning 
i suspect they were watersoaked from the downpour vibration 
from the thunder may have done it i sort of doubt it was in 
fine form and a bolt of terrific lightning sheared it away in one 
stroke he said 
the marble headstones inside the cemetery were undamaged and 
there appeared little damage to the concrete and brick vaults 
themselves 
only seven of the tombs were marked the rest had been closed in 
with plain marble tombstones in the 1960s and 70s because the 
original stones were broken past repair 
the most recent burial date was 1914 the others were all in the 
middle to late 19th century including five family members who died 
from 1848 to 1888 
save our cemeteries has been trying for five years to persuade 
the city to turn over maintenance of the cemetery to the volunteer 
group 
