<TEXT>
a radioactive waste storage tank that 
officials at the hanford nuclear reservation fear might explode 
belched hydrogen gas and the level of waste inside dropped 
officials said monday 
workers had been preparing to take a sample of the tanks 
contents but were waiting for the complex chemical reactions inside 
to create a burp to vent off hydrogen said westinghouse 
hanford co spokesman mike berriochoa 
tank 101sy which is one of 177 tanks at hanford containing 
waste from the production of plutonium for hydrogen bombs vented 
at 530 am sunday according to a company statement 
no environmental contamination occurred the company said the 
gas is released through filters that trap any radioactivity 
company officials have said 
the venting caused waste in the 1 milliongallon tank to drop 
from a depth of 416 inches to about 411 inches by sunday evening 
and a slower decline continued said berriochoa 
thats why we waited until after the burping so we didnt 
risk running into a hydrogen bubble berriochoa said 
the tanks at the reservation in southcentral washington are 
managed by westinghouse for the department of energy 
earlier this year hanford officials said a buildup of hydrogen 
ammonia and nitrous oxide in 20 of the 177 tanks had the potential 
to cause a fire or explosion 
efforts to reduce the danger have been stymied by a lack of 
knowledge about the chemical reactions occurring inside the tanks 
last week ron bliss westinghouse vice president for waste 
management said the company planned to insert a probe into tank 
101sy soon to gather waste samples that will take months to 
analyze 
venting has been occurring about every eight weeks and dates 
from 1979 westinghouse said the last venting occurred in april 
tank 101sy is believed to contain the greatest hydrogen buildup 
because it has the greatest fluctations in waste depth bliss has 
suggested that might be the result of experiments in which large 
amounts of liquid were removed from the tank in the late 1970s in 
an effort to increase its storage capacity 
department officials have said the hydrogen buildup comes from 
organic matter in the tanks decaying leaving the gas trapped 
beneath a hard crust on the surface of the waste 
the doublewalled tank has been under continuous scrutiny since 
the hydrogen buildup problem was announced in march 
the risk of ignition of the hydrogen is considered to be 
low westinghouse repeated in its latest statement 
a critical report last week by the energy departments advisory 
committee on nuclear facility safety raised questions of whether 
the risk of an explosion was as low as officials have contended 
in a letter to energy secretary james watkins panel chairman 
john ahearne declined to characterize the risk of an explosion 
because of the lack of information ahearne said no one knows what 
chemical combinations are in the tanks and that unreliable 
temperature sensors may be misleading 
</TEXT>
