<TEXT>
health maintenance organizations are 
risking patients lives by cutting costs on prescription drugs 
according to a national survey of doctors commissioned by the 
oregon medical association 
cost is affecting quality quality is being sacrificed said 
dr michael graham president of the oregon medical association 
the telephone survey of 700 physicians including 200 in oregon 
was conducted by the gallup organization in january and the results 
were released friday 
graham said monday the survey of cardiologists internists and 
general practitioners showed they were concerned about limits on 
the way they prescribe drugs 
what it amounts to is the hmos and other managedcare 
organizations are restricting the choice of medications graham 
said it restricts the ability of the physician to prescribe 
whats necessary 
graham said nine doctors in the survey reported that a patient 
had died because of costcutting practices by hmos 
i cant give you the details on those nine deaths graham 
said but the physicians felt that the restrictions or lack of 
availability of a drug led to the death of the patient 
he also blamed those practices for slowing the recovery of 
millions of americans suffering from various health problems 
larry freshnock vice president of health care research for 
gallup estimated drug prescription restrictions already may have 
affected 27 million people based on the survey 
however a spokesman for one of the largest hmos in oregon said 
the medical associations claims were exaggerated 
this could scare a lot of people said ron morgan spokesman 
for blue cross of oregon which operates health maintenance of 
oregon 
from our experience with these practices we havent seen any 
problem with the quality of care morgan said you have to 
balance cost containment with finding a way to make drugs available 
to everyone but you just dont sacrifice quality of care 
health maintenance organizations attempt to hold down medical 
costs by paying doctors a fixed amount no matter how many services 
they provide rather than a fee for every service managers of hmos 
also try to hold down costs on medical equipment supplies and 
drugs by seeking the least expensive source 
among the restrictions opposed by doctors and cited in the study 
were 
therapeutic drug interchange a policy that requires 
pharmacists to substitute less expensive drugs when possible 
despite differences in chemical ingredients 
prior authorization which requires physicians affiliated with 
hmos or other managedcare plans to obtain approval before 
prescribing certain drugs 
stepcare protocols a practice that forces doctors to 
prescribe drugs in a fixed order using lowerpriced drugs first 
and more expensive or advanced drugs later 
mandatory generic substitution which requires pharmacies to 
substitute chemically identical generic drugs for brandname drugs 
morgan said that therapeutic drug interchange is illegal for 
outpatients in oregon and health maintenance of oregon does not 
use stepcare protocols 
morgan also said the blue cross hmo does not have a mandatory 
generic substitution policy and its formulary is only a recommended 
list 
representatives of other state and national hmos said they could 
not comment on the survey because they had not seen it 
the most common problem resulting from drug policies according 
to the study was slower recovery from illness followed by failure 
of the drug to work other problems cited by doctors in the survey 
were allergic reactions heart problems pain nausea and 
convulsions 
i dont think theyre trying to implicate any particular drug 
or a particular class of drugs graham said the main point of 
the study is that we think that employers and companies should be 
cautious about signing contracts with restrictive policies 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900806-0133 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
military officials said monday that 
tamil militants shot and hacked to death 23 moslem villagers in 
eastern sri lanka in the second attack on the moslem community in 
three days 
they said rebels of the liberation tigers of tamil eelam raided 
three adjoining villages in ampara district on sunday and rounded 
up the villagers before killing them 
no independent confirmation or rebel version of the government 
account was available 
most communications were severed after the tigers broke a 
13month truce on june 11 and resumed their 7yearold war for 
independence in tamildominated territory in the north and east of 
this indian ocean island nation 
on friday gunmen stormed two mosques at kattankudi village in 
eastern coastal batticaloa district and killed at least 140 
worshipers the government said it blamed tamil tigers 
the militants accuse the moslems of siding with the 
sinhalesedominated government the moslems say they are neutral 
the officials who cannot be identified under briefing rules 
said all the victims were farmers their bodies were dumped in 
paddy fields they said 
