<TEXT>
scientists in oregon and washington have 
discovered two cases 600 miles apart in which a rare northern 
spotted owl has bred with the more common and aggressive barred 
owl producing a new hybrid 
biologists dont know whether the crossbreeding is an isolated 
quirk of nature or the first sign of evolution into a new owl 
species 
but the barred owl is a much hardier owl and there have been 
concerns that the growth in its range could threaten the survival 
of the spotted owl listed as a threatened species in june 
the first sparred owl was confirmed about two weeks ago near 
mount baker in the northern cascade range in washington said eric 
forsman who leads a us forest service spotted owl research team 
the second was confirmed wednesday east of medford in 
southwestern oregon 
i dont know where its going to lead us forsman said 
nobody does 
the us fish and wildlife services designation of the spotted 
owl as threatened cast doubt on the future of logging in old growth 
forests the birds sole habitat 
the barred owl appears similar to the spotted owl except that 
it is somewhat larger has vertical bars on its chest instead of 
brown and white spots and is paler the more aggressive barred owl 
can live in a variety of forest types 
there are only about 2000 known pairs of spotted owls the 
barred owl is common in the united states and canada 
only in the past 15 or 20 years however has the barred owl 
expanded its range south from british columbia into washington 
oregon and northern california where the spotted owl lives 
the barred owls ability to thrive in logged areas of the 
pacific northwest probably explains its invasion of the region 
biologists say 
that ability its aggressive behavior and similar prey make the 
barred owl a competitor with the potential for cutting the spotted 
owl population a fish and wildlife service review team said in its 
recommendation to designate the spotted owl as threatened 
forsman alerted biologists two weeks ago to the first confirmed 
hybrid a male adult found by washington state biologist tom hamer 
a very strange looking bird forsman wrote he said it 
looked like a pale spotted owl but weighed a little more than 1 
pounds more than a male spotted owl 
his call is intermediate between a barred and spotted owl it 
goes hoo hoohoo hoooawww 
the last note is characteristic of the barred owl forsman wrote 
</TEXT>
