<DOCNO> AP900806-0147 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
 
editors note an american missionary family makes its home in 
thailand as protectors of the mlabri one of the worlds smallest 
and most primitive tribes 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the spirits of the yellow leaves 
some of the worlds most primitive and timid tribal people have 
found protection from an unlikely source an american missionary 
family 
eugene long his wife mary and their three children have lived 
among the mlabri for nine years 
while their goal is to christianize the longs have yet to bring 
up god or the bible their more immediate task is to ensure the 
tiny tribes survival and bridge a vast gap between these 
huntergatherers and the 20th century 
there are fewer than 200 mlabri in thailand a small number is 
also believed living deep in the forests of neighboring laos the 
thai population has decreased over the past decade and long says 
further shrinkage would probably mean the tribes extinction 
not long ago all yellow leaves roamed the jungles in small 
family groups eating wild fruits roots and any animals they could 
snare or spear in laos they may still live this way 
myths spread about these furtive people who were said to move 
their homes each time the leaves of their flimsy shelters turned 
yellow 
they wore little more than loincloths and used crude implements 
of a prehistoric age their language which has no written form 
identifies just three colors green red and blue does not 
distinguish between a month and a year and provides for a counting 
system that includes only the words for one two and 
many 
the first known outsider to meet and study the group was 
austrian anthropologist hugo bernatzik who made contact in 1937 
danish scholar jesper trier described them as technologically among 
the most primitive people on earth ancient remnants of australoid 
tribes overwhelmed by the great mongoloid migrations into southeast 
asia from the north 
when long first encountered the yellow leaves he had images of 
cannibals feasting on missionaries while some of its members later 
confided they thought he had come to eat them 
his trail to the tribe had been circuitous at 14 long was a 
selfdescribed hood with a police record the turning point 
came after a close brush with death from alcohol abuse 
after graduating from high school near orlando fla he joined 
the new tribes mission which works with remote littleknown 
tribal groups around the world at its school he met his wife who 
is from muscatine iowa and the couple were sent abroad 
the family moved to the hills of phrae province in northern 
thailand their rough wooden home is located in a lovely valley a 
threemile trek from the nearest village 
the house has no refrigerator or window panes and no television 
to distract allen 14 jared 11 and 7yearold crystal from their 
studies done by correspondence staying healthy is a problem long 
has suffered two bouts with malaria 
initially the mlabri which translates as people of the 
jungle came and went their faces would be expressionless the 
women and children would run away when long approached they lied 
or refused to talk about themselves and their culture even after 
the longs became the first known outsiders to speak their language 
the lives of the yellow leaves are ruled by fear fear of 
human enemies tigers disease the spirits of their animist 
world long said they themselves are passive resolution of 
conflict is flight 
but the widespread disappearance of thailands once great 
forests has shut off their escape hatch and most of their 
traditional sources of livelihood waiting for them as they came 
out of the jungles were the hmong a large more aggressive and 
technologically sophisticated tribe 
long says the hmong treat the yellow leaves like slaves 
luring them with pigs their great dietary obsession and then 
forcing them to work off their pork debt under appalling 
conditions and for abysmally low wages 
now 25 of the tribespeople are living in simple leafroofed 
huts on hillsides around the long home and much of their suspicion 
and fear seems to have subsided 
the family provides meals medicine and basic first aid the 
yellow leaves are given wages for work that ultimately benefits 
them 
long paid the equivalent of 750 to acquire squatters rights 
over several hundred acres of land on which the yellow leaves have 
planted fruit trees sunk fish ponds and reforested denuded strips 
of hillside with teak trees pigs are raised 
long is aware of criticism leveled by some anthropologists that 
his kind of involvement leads to detribalization of people like 
the mlabri 
i want to preserve aspects of their culture ideally i would 
want them to live in undisturbed forests and have them come out to 
see us when they needed help he counters 
but that doesnt seem possible now so we want to give them a 
fair chance in todays world in order to be yellow leaves do they 
have to be slaves of the hmong and die of malaria do they have to 
be extinct if so then yes i am ruining them 
unlike some foreign missionaries in thailand the boyish 
35yearold long and his family all of whom have informally taken 
thai names get favorable coverage from the thai press 
long says the support he has received from phrae provincial 
authorities and the thai military has been good although the thai 
government does not have a formal program to help the yellow 
leaves but serious problems remain he says in neighboring nan 
province where the majority of the mlabri live and where 
exploitation by the hmong continues 
</TEXT>
