<TEXT>
lohengrin cbs masterworks woldemar nelsson conducts the 
bayreuth festival orchestra with karan armstrong peter hofmann 
leif roar siegfreid vogel bernd wiekl and elizabeth connell 
 
wagners lohengrin doesnt make superhuman demands of its 
singers the way some of his later works do but assembling an ideal 
cast isnt easy either 
the lineup for the 1982 bayreuth performance that was recorded 
live by cbs masterworks and has now been transferred to compact 
disc was unfortunately far from ideal 
lohengrin is a romantic fairy tale with nationalistic and 
religious undercurrents elsa the heroine is a maid in distress 
who calls on the man of her dreams for help when she is falsely 
accused of murder 
he arrives in a boat drawn by the famous swan saves her 
reputation and marries her but all their happiness is on one 
condition that she never ask him his name elsa cant bear the 
mystery and soon ruins everything 
the title role is sung here by peter hofmann whose pleasant 
sound and handsome physique made him the most soughtafter of 
wagnerian tenors for a few years in the late 1970s and early 80s 
it wasnt long before his voice grew coarse and strained under the 
pressure of singing roles too strenuous for him 
in this recording he still sounds pretty good but there are 
some forced high notes that in hindsight show he was pushing his 
voice to do things it wasnt meant to do 
elsa is karan armstrong whose thin basically unattractive 
soprano copes adequately with the music but fails to convey the 
warmth and passion that make her one of wagners most treasurable 
heroines 
elizabeth connell as ortrud the sorceress who plants fatal 
seeds of doubt in elsa also has a thin voice but its more 
appealing to the ear than armstrongs 
her husband telramund is sung with little impact by baritone 
leif roar siegfreid vogel is king henry and bernd wiekl who 
would go on to sing more substantial roles at the metropolitan 
opera and elsewhere is heard in the small part of the herald 
woldemar nelsson conducts the bayreuth festival orchestra in a 
fastpaced reading of the score the sound is naturally not as 
wellfocused as with a studio recording but some of the excitement 
of a live performance comes through 
by mike silverman associated press writer 
</TEXT>
