<TEXT>
on his 200yearold farm in the mountains of 
western maine author michael rothschild likes to pick apples from 
the orchard grind them up and press them into cider 
the cider is difficult to drink no water or sugar is added it 
catches in your throat the first time and makes you shake your head 
and squeeze your eyes shut as if you had dipped your tongue in a 
spoonful of vinegar 
rothschilds writing goes down just as hard the stories from 
his second collection wondermonger 1795 viking need to 
be read a few pages at a time with long pauses in between unless 
you have an intricate knowledge of maine folklore theyre 
difficult to understand at first and you may not bother trying 
again 
but its like drinking pure cider read the toad two or 
three times grab hold of the words as if each one hangs from the 
tip of a branch and you get caught up in simple miracles such as 
how wide a snakes mouth can open as well as the authors pleasure 
in telling the story 
youre putting a terrible pressure on the person and i think 
youd better have something where if the person does read you 
again youd better deliver rothschild explained between deep 
puffs of cigarettes at his publishers offices i think readers 
will be taken to a place where theyre not taken in fiction anymore 
there are people who talk to a kid and say this kids smart 
ill talk to him on the level of 7 and this kids dumb ill 
talk to him with a 3 
but i dont change my vocabulary or my expressions when i 
write im not writing for this person or for that person maybe it 
would be better if i was writing to appeal to an audience in a 
certain way 
so imagine being dropped in a forest of pine in the dead of 
winter with snow falling as if sifted through the clouds and the 
north wind pulling at the trees there are no maps or tour guides 
just a copy of wondermonger to safely get you home 
winter fostered neighborliness among the dennedup settlers of 
tantrattle he writes in the title story just as deer to 
survive the depth of snow and boreal winds yard beneath a 
sheltering stand of cedar and paw after browse within the 
steepwalled confines of their maze so the scattered families 
tunneled out from storm upon december storm to call upon friends 
or with new fervor and frequency congregated sunday morning and 
wednesday evenings at the reverend cawkins meeting house 
now rothschild admits he has a hard time explaining what that 
means even his mother complains she doesnt understand but 
compare it to looking at a landscape painting steepwalled 
confines and a sheltering stand of cedar are the story 
rothschilds fiction isnt about characters getting from one place 
to another its about the places themselves 
when theres a terrible blizzard the master blizzard of the 
winter there are people that stay by their stoves and i suppose 
there are some people that like to go out and bundle up and go out 
because they like to see whats going on rothschild said 
for better or worse im one of those people when there are 
rivers breaking up and ice floes large as cars i ruffle up my hair 
and my eyes roll back in my head and i feel great 
the nine stories of wondermonger can be divided between 
tales of the awful and the aweinspiring between shotguns and 
bleeding dogs and pregnant women and mystical children 
they run chronologically starting in colonial times with the 
title story and leading up the present and beyond with a land 
without fossils the toad lasts just three pages 
wondermonger runs over 60 and only a land without fossils 
in which a father contemplates the maps drawn by his 5yearold 
son resembles the authors own life 
rothschild was born in maine in 1947 hes a rugged looking man 
ernest borgnine with a ponytail and between tending to the 
farm raising four children sculpting and making trips to china 
he hasnt had much time to write his first set of stories 
rhapsody of a hermit was published in 1973 and the back of the 
book promises a novel that has yet to be completed 
his friends include woodsmen who remove their hats in front of 
his sculptures of naked women and an elderly neighbor who responds 
to the word art by asking art who 
so rather than attend writers conferences or philosophize at 
cocktail parties rothschild can be found setting snares or 
reading nathanial hawthorne to children on july 4 or helping a pig 
give birth in the middle of the night 
he dismisses suggestions that staying on the farm means writing 
in the wilderness just looking at the moon is inspiration for 
rothschild a man who has no interest in living in a big city who 
sees chatting up authors as unnecessary as going to town to buy a 
carton of apple juice 
people ask me why i write in a void and it always seems 
peculiar when i think about it rothschild said because im 
surrounded with people who are living their lives farmers and 
millworkers people living in the hills trying to hang onto their 
farms people of all ages kids and animals 
it seems like an absolute plenitude the opposite of the void 
now a group of artists talking about writing or talking about 
painting that seems to me almost dead center void 
</TEXT>
