<TEXT>
the federal reserve board will lower 
shortterm interest rates soon to stimulate a tottering economy 
that faces a damaging new blow from higher oil prices resulting 
from iraqs invasion of kuwait analysts predicted monday 
an economy that already had slowed to barely perceptible growth 
during the first half of the year is threatened further by 
embargoes imposed by the united states and many other western 
nations on imports of iraqi and kuwaiti oil 
as a result many analsysts said the federal reserve probably 
will nudge its federal funds rate down from 8 percent to 7 percent 
to stimulate growth 
the federal funds rate the interest charged by the fed for 
overnight loans to banks has remained high for more than a year as 
the central bank sought to slow the economy and reduce inflationary 
pressures 
historically the fed has actively fought inflation only as 
long as the economy was not threatened by recession economist 
samuel d kahan wrote in the current issue of perspectives the 
fuji securities inc weekly commentary 
when it appears that the us economy is about to fall into a 
recession the fed must shift its policy efforts he said 
recent economic releases suggest that we have entered this zone 
and we look for the fed to shift its policy directive and emphasize 
economic growth 
we expect the fed to ease the federal funds rate to 7 percent 
any day soon said mark m zandi an economist with regional 
financial associates in west chester pa 
if the united states manages to escape a recession induced by 
middle east developments some analysts said higher energy costs 
combined with rising unemployment would produce something similar 
to the stagflation of the late 1970s 
its wont be as severe but its an unpleasant 
combination said donald straszheim chief economist with merrill 
lynch capital markets in new york 
charles schultze former chairman of the white house council of 
economic advisers in the carter administration suggested during a 
weekend tv interview that the iraqi invasion could produce a mild 
recession if nothing else happens 
many private economists believe the stagnant economy is as close 
to nogrowth as possible without actually being negative right 
now were skirting the edge of a recession says robert g 
dederick chief economist of northern trust co of chicago the 
economy is just creeping ahead 
the gross national product the nations total output of goods 
and services rose just 12 percent in the second quarter some 
economists said the economy had worsened in july even before the 
iraqi invasion 
however zandi and some other analysts noted that business 
inventories one of the classic portents of a recession had 
declined since the first of the year 
in other major recessions businesses accumulated big 
inventories zandi said resulting in production declines and job 
layoffs to correct the situation 
zandi predicted that unemployment will reach about 6 percent by 
years end the jobless rate rose to 56 percent in july the 
highest level in two years it exceeded 10 percent during the last 
recession in 198182 
