grain and soybean futures prices closed higher 
monday on the chicago board of trade paced by sharp gains in corn 
and soybeans as the surging crude oil and gold markets stoked 
inflation fears 
the jump of more than 3 per barrel in crude oil futures also 
sparked speculation that the soviet union which exports oil to 
european countries might soon have more money to spend on grain 
imports said joel karlin a grain market analyst with research 
department inc in chicago 
there are ideas that the higher crude prices will give them a 
few more dollars to play with and putting two and two together 
theyll have more to spend on food karlin said 
crudeoil traders bid prices up dramatically monday in reaction 
to the iraqi occupation of kuwait and the potential for further 
armed conflict in the middle east 
karlin said unseasonably cool overnight temperatures in the 
midwest revived concerns about the possibility of early frost 
damage to soybeans which added further support 
but karlin said market fundamentals remained bearish for 
example the agriculture departments weekly grain 
