<TEXT>
the dollar lost more ground monday against all 
major foreign currencies except the japanese yen amid speculation 
that recent signs of economic weakness will lead to lower us 
interest rates 
but the decline was tempered by uncertainties about iraqs 
occupation of persian gulf neighbor kuwait those worries made 
traders reluctant to push the dollar lower because of the 
possibility that a military outbreak could send investors in search 
of the perceived safety of the currency 
gold prices climbed benefiting from its status as a haven 
against international turmoil and a hedge against inflation 
the dollar moved sharply lower as trading resumed in the united 
states pushing the dollar toward its lowest level in 2 years 
against the german mark but the dollar later recovered somewhat as 
rumors swirled about what may happen overnight in the persian gulf 
this is all emotional trading said liliana nealon first 
vice president at the new york office of the union bank of 
switzerland 
she said traders expect interest rates to fall in the united 
states in the wake of last weeks unemployment report that 
indicated the economy may be headed toward a recession increasing 
chances that the federal reserve would encourage lower interest 
rates 
but she said they are fearful that an eruption of new military 
action in the persian gulf would drive the dollar higher because 
investors view it as the safest to hold during international 
turmoil 
president bush said monday he was ruling out nothing at all 
including a military blockade to choke off iraqi trade in response 
to iraqs invasion of kuwait last week 
the invasion has led to sharply higher oil prices around the 
world and triggered a big drop monday in world stock prices 
the dollar gained against the japanese yen largely because the 
japanese economy is seen as vulnerable to oil price hikes since 
japan depends almost entirely on imported oil 
by the end of trading in new york the dollar had risen to 
