<DOCNO> AP900806-0217 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the chairman of a house energy subcommittee 
called monday on the bush administration in coordination with 
japan and europe to start pumping oil from emergency government 
reserves to halt the price spiral brought on by iraqs invasion of 
kuwait 
the strategic petroleum reserve has to be used to make sure 
shortages dont show up to short the market and protect the 
consumer said rep philip r sharp chairman of the house energy 
and commerce committees subcommittee on energy and power 
just before it adjourned saturday congress extended bushs 
authority to begin drawing upon the 587millionbarrel us reserve 
stored in salt caverns along the louisianatexas coast while it is 
on vacation for the rest of august 
sharp dind said a flooding of market with government 
reserves from emergency stockpiles in the united states europe and 
japan could stem rapidly escalating oil prices on the world market 
since thursday the price the west texas intermediate crude has 
jumped to more than 28 a barrel as of the close of trading monday 
the highest level in five years 
an embargo or blockade of oil from kuwait and iraq by cutting 
off pipelines in turkey and saudi arabia as advocated by the bush 
administration would put further upward pressure on prices 
currently between 35 million to 45 million barrels of oil per 
day about 15 percent of the worlds supply move through those 
pipelines and via tankers passing through the straits of hormuz 
the energy department has the capacity to pump a maximum 3 
million barrels a day from its emergency reserve a roughly 
200day supply 
a more likely scenario according to government and private 
experts would be to pump between 1 million and 2 million barrels 
per day from the us reserve in coordination with similar draws 
from allies government reserves 
deputy energy secretary henson moore said last week the bush 
administration has no intention to use the reserve only to stop an 
increase in oil prices 
the strategic petroleum reserve is not designed as a pricing 
mechanism he told reporters last thursday it was designed as 
a reserve of needed oil in this country not to set prices 
the administration of bushs predecessor ronald reagan had 
reached agreements with energy ministers in japan and the european 
community in the middle 1980s to coordinate early draws of their 
respective reserves if a disruption in world supplies set off a 
price spiral 
the reserve was established as as rainyday stockpile in 
response to the 197374 arab oil embargo it has been tapped only 
once before in a congressionally ordered 1985 test drawdown of 2 
million barrels auctioned off to oil companies 
meanwhile lawmakers hastily scheduled hearings for tuesday on 
what they said was price gouging by the oil companies wholesalers 
and service station dealers 
sen richard bryan dnev said oil companies have gone on a 
feeding frenzy despite nearrecord stockpiles on hand the oil 
companies are playing the old game heads they win tails you 
lose he said 
