<TEXT>
here is a brief rundown on how the rapidly changing events in 
the persian gulf rippled through the markets monday and affected 
other business and economic news 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
panicky traders scoured the world for oil because they feared 
shortages and pushed the price to the highest levels in five 
years on the new york mercantile exchange the price of key west 
texas intermediate crude jumped 356 a barrel to settle at 2805 
prices for refined products such as heating oil and gasoline also 
surged dramatically 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the impact of rising oil prices on the already weak us economy 
pummeled wall street again where stocks tumbled and the widely 
watched dow jones industrial average took the worst oneday spill 
since the october 1989 minicrash the index of 30 bluechip 
stocks ended down 9331 points or 332 percent at 271634 in 
the bond market a sensitive barometer of the economys health 
most prices fell sharply and interest rates rose on fears of higher 
inflation but those same fears strengthened the price of gold 
historically considered a safe haven investment the dollar 
weakened against most other key currencies 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
from airport ticket counters to gas pumps nationwide consumers 
began paying for the uncertainty in the oil market pan american 
world airways became the second major carrier after northwest to 
jack up prices because of rising fuel costs gasoline prices at 
service stations were up as much as 14 cents a gallon from levels 
prior to iraqs seizure of kuwait last week provoking cries of 
price gouging several states said they would investigate alleged 
profiteering in washington the chairman of a house energy 
subcommittee called on the bush administration to tap emergency 
government oil reserves created after the 1970s arab oilprice 
shocks in order to halt the latest price spiral 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
many economists speculated that the federal reserve board would 
lower shortterm interest rates soon to stimulate the economy and 
forestall a recession caused by the new blow of higher oil prices 
some suggested the central bank will nudge interest rates lower 
through its influence over the federal funds rate the interest 
charged on overnight loans to banks 
