midnight expiration approached 
ballots in a strikeauthorization vote were being counted late 
monday said dan j backstead president of the communications 
workers of americas united telegraph workers bargaining council 
the cwa has been pushing for higher wage increases the union 
also opposes the companys plan to shift some medical premiums to 
workers and add parttime employees 
negotiations between the union and western union traditionally 
go to the last day of a contract said company spokesman warren 
bechtel 
the union opposed the companys offer of a 25 percent annual 
wage increase over two years but have not countered with another 
offer beckstead said late monday in a telephone interview from the 
negotiating site in virginia beach va western union is based in 
upper saddle river 
neither bechtel nor beckstead would provide specific details 
about how the insurance costs would be shared but bechtel said the 
company proposed union employees payments match those made by 
nonunion workers 
the union similarly resisted the companys proposals to merge 
the duties of operators and customer relations clerks and to 
increase the number of parttime employees not entitled to benefits 
under the union contract 
the company was prepared to use management and 1000 recently 
trained temporary workers to keep operating in the event of a 
walkout bechtel said 
for most of its 140 years western union held a monopoly on 
telegram service in the united states in recent years western 
union has diversified into other communications businesses 
union workers last struck western union in 1985 for 10 days 
a 1971 labor dispute took 57 days to settle and another in 1952 
stretched on for 53 days beckstead said 
