<TEXT>
oil prices leaped to their highest levels in 
nearly five years and the dow jones industrial average took its 
biggest dive since last october as the financial markets continued 
to wrestle monday with the persian gulf crisis 
the dollar also fell sharply against most currencies in foreign 
exchange shedding its historical role as a safe haven during times 
of political turmoil 
money flowed instead into treasury bills among the most secure 
shortterm investments available 
we have a selling panic going on in the stock and bond markets 
and a flight to quality to t bills said edward yardeni chief 
economist for prudentialbache securities inc when investors are 
nervous they tend to pull back 
on wall street the dow jones industrial average the 
bestknown barometer of the stock market slid 9331 points to 
close at 271634 after slipping as much as 105 points earlier in 
the day 
the plunge the biggest since last octobers minicrash 
tripped socalled circuit breakers designed by the nations 
financial markets to cushion market declines in stocks and stock 
index futures 
declining issues far outpaced advances among stocks listed on 
the new york stock exchange 
mondays drop extended a weeklong slide in the market that has 
erased just just over 200 points from the dow average 
in oildependent japan the nikkei stock average of 225 selected 
issues closed at 2859953 points down 91623 points or 31 
percent in britain the financial timesstock exchange 100share 
index dropped 644 points or 29 percent to 22202 
in early trading tuesday the nikkei was down another 45728 
points or 16 percent at 2814225 
in the united states traders blamed the rout on continued 
worries that sharply higher oil prices stemming from iraqs 
invasion of neighboring kuwait last week could trigger higher 
inflation and push the nation into a recession the economy is in 
pretty bad shape now this could make things worse yardeni said 
oil prices continued their upward trend monday with no end in 
sight on the new york mercantile exchange the september contract 
for west texas intermediate soared 356 to settle at 2805 a 
42gallon barrel 
it was the highest level for the the benchmark grade of us 
crude since august 1985 when the price reached 2808 per barrel 
among refined petroleum products wholesale unleaded gasoline 
jumped 934 cents to 8152 cents a gallon wholesale home heating 
oil was up 897 cents to 7555 cents 
market observers said that if the united states and its allies 
move aggressively to end the conflict in the middle east the 
economic impact may be minimal but if allowed to linger for weeks 
the crisis could erode business confidence resulting in job 
layoffs or lower production the ingredients for a recession 
were in the hands of a very very unpredictable ruthless 
madman running iraq so most peoples investment portfolios are 
being held hostage to what iraqi president saddam hussein does 
next yardeni said 
part of the nations economic future also hinges on the federal 
reserves credit policies economists said 
the policy options were not good even without thinking about 
what hostilities lie on the horizon said robert a brusca chief 
financial economist for nikko securities co international the 
fed has these conflicting signals 
a move by the fed to lower interest rates could stimulate the 
economy but it could also further aggravate the inflation outlook 
speculation that the fed will cut rates helped push the dollar 
lower against all major currencies except the japanes yen among 
the dollars biggest drop was against the german mark where it 
slipped to 2year lows 
interest rate concerns coupled with worries about oil prices 
contributed to mondays drop in the bond market 
investors unwilling to lock their money into anything long 
range sold longterm treasury bonds the governments bellwether 
30year issue for instance plunged about 2 points or 25 per 
1000 face amount the drop was far less dramatic in shorterterm 
bonds and notes 
also hurting bonds were concerns about the budget deficit and 
how it might be affected by the mideast turmoil 
with higher oil prices you wont have an energy tax as 
lawmakers have discussed and you wont see cuts in defense 
spending said maury harris chief economist for painewebber inc 
</TEXT>
